## 1. Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)

### How it happens
API endpoints often use **object identifiers** to retrieve data. BOLA (similar to **IDOR**) occurs when a user provides an ID they aren't authorized to see, and the server fails to validate ownership of that resource at the code level.

### Impact
Unauthorized access leads to data leakage and account takeovers, resulting in financial loss and brand damage.

### Practical Example
The endpoint fails to check if the requester is authorized to see the specific Employee ID.
![BOLA Vulnerable](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/RyanO89/Product-Security-journey/main/images/BOLA_V.png)



**The Fix:** Developer "Bob" implements an authorization mechanism using **Access Tokens** in the header.
![BOLA Secured](../images/BOLA_S.png)
*Adding the token correctly produces a **403 Forbidden** error for unauthorized requests.*

### Mitigation
* Implement strict access controls and check user hierarchies.
* Use unpredictable, random values (UUIDs) for tokens.

