## 3. Excessive Data Exposure

### How it happens
Developers often return a full object from the database, assuming the **front-end** will filter the data. An attacker can intercept the full API response to see sensitive hidden fields.

### Impact
Attackers sniff traffic to find account numbers, phone numbers, and access tokens not intended for public view.

### Practical Example
The endpoint `/apirule3/comment_v/{id}` fetches all database info (location, device info) instead of just the comment text.
![EDA Vulnerable](../images/EDA_V.png)

**The Fix:** The updated `/apirule3/comment_s/{id}` returns only necessary information.
![EDA Secured](../images/EDA_S.png)

### Mitigation
* Never rely on the front-end to filter sensitive data.
* Avoid generic methods like `to_string()` or `to_json()`.

